The bottom line with
gold is, until we

00:16:57.120 --> 00:17:01.750 align:middle line:84%
see-- until we see an imminence
of a new market crash,

00:17:01.750 --> 00:17:03.810 align:middle line:84%
which we don't see
yet, we're going

00:17:03.810 --> 00:17:06.900 align:middle line:84%
to see gold hovering in the
neighborhood of this $1,100

00:17:06.900 --> 00:17:08.290 align:middle line:90%
to $1,200 range.

00:17:08.290 --> 00:17:10.740 align:middle line:84%
I don't think there's
really much room for it

00:17:10.740 --> 00:17:14.400 align:middle line:84%
to go any lower than that, given
the cost of gold manufacturing

00:17:14.400 --> 00:17:17.030 align:middle line:84%
or the bottom line
costs of bringing gold

00:17:17.030 --> 00:17:18.770 align:middle line:90%
to the surface right now.

00:17:18.770 --> 00:17:21.220 align:middle line:84%
I think you're pretty
much at a bottom.

00:17:21.220 --> 00:17:23.569 align:middle line:84%
Now, for people
who are considering

00:17:23.569 --> 00:17:26.420 align:middle line:84%
what to do as an
investor as a hedge,

00:17:26.420 --> 00:17:30.240 align:middle line:84%
I would be very cautious
to jump into this right

00:17:30.240 --> 00:17:31.920 align:middle line:90%
now as a hedge for people.

00:17:31.920 --> 00:17:36.140 align:middle line:84%
Because you've got a scenario
with this Federal Reserve--

00:17:36.140 --> 00:17:38.100 align:middle line:84%
remember, there's no
commanding legal authority

00:17:38.100 --> 00:17:39.140 align:middle line:90%
in the Federal Reserve.

00:17:39.140 --> 00:17:40.680 align:middle line:90%
Janet Yellen can do anything.

00:17:40.680 --> 00:17:44.870 align:middle line:84%
She's reading the ti leaves, and
they use all the common metrics

00:17:44.870 --> 00:17:47.390 align:middle line:84%
that they have to determine
how they're going to do this.

00:17:47.390 --> 00:17:50.175 align:middle line:84%
But the bottom line is, there
is no inflationary cycle

00:17:50.175 --> 00:17:51.300 align:middle line:90%
that they're worried about.

00:17:51.300 --> 00:17:52.390 align:middle line:90%
It's deflation.

00:17:52.390 --> 00:17:54.089 align:middle line:84%
As long as deflation
is on the horizon,

00:17:54.089 --> 00:17:56.130 align:middle line:84%
they are not going to
raise those interest rates.

00:17:56.130 --> 00:17:57.940 align:middle line:84%
They're too afraid
that they could drive

00:17:57.940 --> 00:17:59.540 align:middle line:90%
the country into a recession.

00:17:59.540 --> 00:18:01.770 align:middle line:84%
And remember, we're heading
into an election cycle.

00:18:01.770 --> 00:18:04.850 align:middle line:84%
And typically, there's a chicken
in every pot during an election

00:18:04.850 --> 00:18:05.350 align:middle line:90%
cycle.

00:18:05.350 --> 00:18:08.250 align:middle line:84%
And they're not going to
want to mess with, you've got

00:18:08.250 --> 00:18:09.500 align:middle line:90%
a good thing going right now.

00:18:09.500 --> 00:18:10.890 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I mean, how long
has it been since they've

00:18:10.890 --> 00:18:11.950 align:middle line:90%
raised interest rates?

00:18:11.950 --> 00:18:13.320 align:middle line:90%
It's been years, hasn't it?

